<script>
	import { CodeBlock, Callout, Quiz } from '$lib/components/lesson';

	const componentTest = `import { render } from 'vitest-browser-svelte';
import { expect, test } from 'vitest';
import Button from '$lib/components/ui/Button.svelte';

test('danger intent applies the danger classes', async () => {
  const screen = render(Button, { intent: 'danger', children: () => 'Delete' });
  const button = screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Delete' });
  await expect.element(button).toBeInTheDocument();
  expect(button.element().className).toContain('bg-red-600');
});`;

	const a11yTest = `import { render } from 'vitest-browser-svelte';
import { expect, test } from 'vitest';
import IconButton from '$lib/components/ui/IconButton.svelte';

test('icon-only button exposes an accessible name', async () => {
  const screen = render(IconButton, { label: 'Close' });
  // queryable by its accessible name → screen readers can find it too
  await expect.element(screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Close' })).toBeInTheDocument();
});`;
</script>

# Testing UI

Styling rarely breaks loudly — it breaks *quietly*: a variant stops applying, a focus ring vanishes,
an icon button loses its label. Tests turn those silent regressions into red builds.

## What's worth testing in a UI

You can't (and shouldn't) snapshot every pixel. Test the things that *matter and regress*:

- **Behaviour:** does clicking toggle, submit, open?
- **Variant contracts:** does `intent="danger"` actually produce the danger styling?
- **Accessibility:** is every control reachable by role and name?

## Component tests with vitest-browser-svelte

This course is configured with Vitest's browser mode and `vitest-browser-svelte`, which renders real
components in a real browser.

<CodeBlock language="typescript" filename="Button.svelte.spec.ts" code={componentTest} />

## Accessibility as an assertion

Querying by **role and accessible name** is a two-for-one: it tests behaviour *and* proves the element
is accessible (if the test can't find it by name, neither can a screen reader).

<CodeBlock language="typescript" filename="IconButton.svelte.spec.ts" code={a11yTest} />

## Pure logic stays fast

Logic without a DOM (your `cn()`, variant maps, navigation helpers) gets plain, fast unit tests — like
the `navigation.spec.ts` and `cn.spec.ts` already in this project.

<Callout type="insight" title="Test the contract, not the implementation">

The trap in UI testing is asserting on *implementation details* — exact class strings, DOM structure —
which makes tests brittle and refactors painful. Aim higher: test the **contract** the component
promises. "A danger button is announced as a button named X and signals danger" is a contract; "div >
span.bg-red-600" is an implementation detail. Querying by role/name (as above) tests the contract
*and* accessibility at once. When you set testing strategy for a team, push toward
behaviour-and-contract tests and away from snapshot-everything — you'll get suites that catch real
regressions without screaming on every legitimate change.

</Callout>

<Callout type="tip" title="Run tests in CI, not just locally">

Tests only protect you if they run on every PR. The next lesson wires `pnpm test` (plus lint and
type-check) into CI so nothing red can merge.

</Callout>

## Knowledge check

<Quiz
	question="Why query elements by role and accessible name in component tests?"
	options={[
		{ text: 'It’s faster than CSS selectors', correct: false },
		{ text: 'It tests behaviour and proves accessibility simultaneously', correct: true },
		{ text: 'It avoids needing a browser', correct: false },
		{ text: 'It snapshots the DOM', correct: false }
	]}
	explanation="If a test can find a control by role+name, so can assistive tech — the query doubles as an a11y check."
/>

## Recap

- Test **behaviour, variant contracts, and accessibility** — not every pixel.
- Use **vitest-browser-svelte** for components; plain unit tests for pure logic.
- Query by **role/name** to test contract + a11y together; avoid brittle snapshots.
